From r@oknz @end|ng |rom gm@||@com  Fri May 23 08:00:52 2025
From: r@oknz @end|ng |rom gm@||@com (Richard O'Keefe)
Date: Fri, 23 May 2025 18:00:52 +1200
Subject: [R] Why is there no macro facility for R?
In-Reply-To: <DM6PR03MB504900736828959A8E5AF1B6E298A@DM6PR03MB5049.namprd03.prod.outlook.com>
References: <DM6PR03MB504900736828959A8E5AF1B6E298A@DM6PR03MB5049.namprd03.prod.outlook.com>
Message-ID: <CABcYAdKM6t2itbhcPyZqKFR--wBcjPELjJ51yMPdT4Ls7dmbYA@mail.gmail.com>

R is closely modelled on S.  S was always designed to interoperate
well with UNIX tools.
Unix has always had cpp (for c-like languages) and m4
(general-purpose) as outboard macro processors.
Then too, the classic S Blue Book explained how to do "computing on
the language'",
see section 5 of R Language Definition,
so the AST-based macro processor for R is called (drum roll please) R.

